WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.690 --> 00:00:05.390
Prof: Okay,
let's get started.

00:00:05.390 --> 00:00:11.000
So last time we looked at
methane and ammonia,

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.650
and saw something interesting
about molecular orbitals:

00:00:14.650 --> 00:00:18.300
we could give them the same
name as atomic orbitals;

00:00:18.300 --> 00:00:22.127
that is, if we,
especially if we look at a low

00:00:22.127 --> 00:00:26.720
electron density contour of the
molecular orbitals,

00:00:26.720 --> 00:00:32.070
we see that what it looks like
is an atom where the nucleus is

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:33.650
split into pieces.
 

00:00:33.650 --> 00:00:34.440
Right?
 

00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:39.005
Now that splitting into pieces
changes the potential energy for

00:00:39.005 --> 00:00:40.110
the electron.
 

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:42.290
So you expect that to distort
the orbital.

00:00:42.290 --> 00:00:45.949
The electrons will move in the
directions that pieces of the

00:00:45.949 --> 00:00:47.190
nucleus have gone.
 

00:00:47.190 --> 00:00:51.313
But then, in addition to
potential energy controlling the

00:00:51.313 --> 00:00:54.700
shape of orbitals,
kinetic energy also does.

00:00:54.700 --> 00:00:57.040
And that's the same thing as it
is in an atom.

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:00.390
You have a thing with no nodes,
a thing with one node --

00:01:00.390 --> 00:01:04.055
and when you have one node you
can have either a spherical

00:01:04.055 --> 00:01:05.863
node,
or a planar node,

00:01:05.863 --> 00:01:08.680
and there can be three planar
nodes;

00:01:08.680 --> 00:01:10.920
so a 2s and three
2p's.

00:01:10.920 --> 00:01:14.879
Exactly the same considerations
apply in a molecular orbital as

00:01:14.879 --> 00:01:16.349
in an atomic orbital.
 

00:01:16.349 --> 00:01:19.367
You have the kinetic energy,
which comes with curvature,

00:01:19.367 --> 00:01:20.739
which comes with nodes.
 

00:01:20.739 --> 00:01:25.239
Now, as you split the nucleus
up and pull pieces in different

00:01:25.239 --> 00:01:27.223
directions,
it doesn't have the same

00:01:27.223 --> 00:01:29.480
symmetry it had when it was all
together in the nucleus,

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:30.860
a spherical kind of symmetry.
 

00:01:30.860 --> 00:01:32.780
So the nodes get distorted.
 

00:01:32.780 --> 00:01:34.300
But still you can see them
there.

00:01:34.300 --> 00:01:38.706
And we saw them last time and
went through all the occupied

00:01:38.706 --> 00:01:42.810
and vacant valance orbitals of
ammonia and methane,

00:01:42.810 --> 00:01:45.430
and saw how they looked like
atomic orbitals.

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:48.572
This, not surprisingly,
because it's so fundamental,

00:01:48.572 --> 00:01:51.224
the potential energy and the
kinetic energy,

00:01:51.224 --> 00:01:52.950
applies to every system.
 

00:01:52.950 --> 00:01:56.748
It applies to you,
viewed as a single atom --

00:01:56.748 --> 00:01:57.440
right?
 

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:00.239
-- with a zillion electrons.
 

00:02:00.239 --> 00:02:00.900
Okay?
 

00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:04.310
But pieces have moved around,
so the orbitals change.

00:02:04.310 --> 00:02:07.689
We'll look at two more
complicated cases and then we'll

00:02:07.689 --> 00:02:10.818
get on to a different way of
looking at bonding.

00:02:10.818 --> 00:02:12.770
So we'll look at ethane and
methanol.

00:02:12.770 --> 00:02:16.177
And we use -- I didn't tell you
last time, explicitly,

00:02:16.177 --> 00:02:18.879
where I got the molecular
orbitals from.

00:02:18.879 --> 00:02:20.370
I got them from my laptop.
 

00:02:20.370 --> 00:02:23.274
There's a program -- the
particular one is called

00:02:23.274 --> 00:02:26.054
Spartan,
that I use -- and it calculates

00:02:26.054 --> 00:02:28.508
what molecular orbitals look
like,

00:02:28.508 --> 00:02:31.938
using approximate molecular
orbital (that is,

00:02:31.938 --> 00:02:35.370
Schrödinger equation kind
of) theory.

00:02:35.370 --> 00:02:38.770
Okay, so let's just look at the
ones of ethane and methanol.

00:02:38.770 --> 00:02:43.128
Now both of these have seven
pairs of valence electrons.

00:02:43.128 --> 00:02:47.186
There are also core electrons,
and if we were looking at the

00:02:47.186 --> 00:02:50.830
orbitals for all the electrons,
we'd include those.

00:02:50.830 --> 00:02:54.229
And exactly how we're going to
count those --

00:02:54.229 --> 00:02:56.098
you could do it one way or the
other --

00:02:56.098 --> 00:02:58.199
whether you consider the core
electrons,

00:02:58.199 --> 00:03:01.092
the 1s electrons to just
be part of the nucleus and then

00:03:01.092 --> 00:03:03.658
treat the rest as the electrons
you're interested in;

00:03:03.658 --> 00:03:08.020
or whether you want to count
the core electrons too.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:10.745
You can do it either way,
but what you analogize to what

00:03:10.745 --> 00:03:13.620
depends on whether you count
them as part of the nuclei.

00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:17.796
So anyhow, we're going to
compare these molecular orbitals

00:03:17.796 --> 00:03:22.266
to the atomic orbitals of argon,
which has also seven electron

00:03:22.266 --> 00:03:23.000
pairs.
 

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.639
Okay, so there's the 2s
orbital.

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:29.490
I'm going to start with that,
because I'm going to pretend

00:03:29.490 --> 00:03:32.340
that that red part is the core
-- that there's a 1s

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:33.740
which is core electrons.
 

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:37.464
But in this case -- here's my
pedantic note on this

00:03:37.464 --> 00:03:39.360
subject which I just added.
 

00:03:39.360 --> 00:03:42.913
So if you have -- before we had
just one heavy atom,

00:03:42.913 --> 00:03:45.562
carbon in methane,
nitrogen in ammonia.

00:03:45.562 --> 00:03:46.258
Right?
 

00:03:46.258 --> 00:03:48.882
So there was one 1s
orbital.

00:03:48.882 --> 00:03:49.500
Right?
 

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:54.110
Now we have two heavy atoms,
carbon and carbon in methane,

00:03:54.110 --> 00:03:56.699
carbon and oxygen in methanol.
 

00:03:56.699 --> 00:04:01.461
So there are two heavy atoms
and therefore two boring core

00:04:01.461 --> 00:04:02.378
orbitals.
 

00:04:02.378 --> 00:04:05.120
So for purposes of making
analogies,

00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:08.080
we'll use the atomic 1s
orbital,

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:11.258
of the atom that we're
analogizing things to,

00:04:11.258 --> 00:04:14.258
to stand for all the molecular
core orbitals.

00:04:14.258 --> 00:04:15.490
You can do it any way you want
to.

00:04:15.490 --> 00:04:16.870
We're not really interested in
that.

00:04:16.870 --> 00:04:18.149
We're interested in the valence
orbitals.

00:04:18.149 --> 00:04:20.887
So whether I start with the
1s or the 2s

00:04:20.887 --> 00:04:23.420
depends on how I'm handling the
core electrons;

00:04:23.420 --> 00:04:24.629
it's not a big deal.
 

00:04:24.629 --> 00:04:28.845
Anyhow, let's pretend it's the
2s of argon here,

00:04:28.845 --> 00:04:33.451
and we're going to compare it
with this lowest valence level

00:04:33.451 --> 00:04:35.949
molecular orbital of ethane.
 

00:04:35.949 --> 00:04:40.971
Now we can -- as I do this,
on the left side of the

00:04:40.971 --> 00:04:44.889
pictures I'm going to show one
view,

00:04:44.889 --> 00:04:49.468
and then, because it's more
complicated than methane and

00:04:49.468 --> 00:04:52.052
ammonia were,
I'm going to also show a

00:04:52.052 --> 00:04:53.879
picture rotated by ninety
degrees.

00:04:53.879 --> 00:04:56.807
So I'm going to rotate around
that axis, and on the right I'll

00:04:56.807 --> 00:04:58.920
show a different view of the
same orbital.

00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:02.298
Okay, so that's the lowest
valence level molecular orbital

00:05:02.298 --> 00:05:03.009
of ethane.
 

00:05:03.009 --> 00:05:07.769
And it's not very exciting;
it's just a distorted sphere.

00:05:07.769 --> 00:05:09.800
And you can see the way in
which it's distorted.

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:12.137
It's distorted vertically,
because the two carbons are

00:05:12.137 --> 00:05:14.841
pulled apart;
so it's got sort of a narrow

00:05:14.841 --> 00:05:15.790
waist to it.
 

00:05:15.790 --> 00:05:20.357
And then it's pulled out,
where each of the protons left

00:05:20.357 --> 00:05:24.259
the middle atom to come out and
be hydrogens.

00:05:24.259 --> 00:05:24.879
Okay?
 

00:05:24.879 --> 00:05:29.250
Now if we look at methanol,
it'll be a little different.

00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:32.480
Can you anticipate how it might
be different if,

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:35.985
on the bottom we'll have CH_3
again, but on the top,

00:05:35.985 --> 00:05:39.490
instead of having CH_3,
we're going to have OH.

00:05:39.490 --> 00:05:42.610
How do you think it might be
different, in the way it looks?

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:46.144
Student:  It might be
skewed more towards the OH

00:05:46.144 --> 00:05:48.855
because oxygen is --
Prof: Okay,

00:05:48.855 --> 00:05:51.470
so oxygen has a bigger nuclear
charge.

00:05:51.470 --> 00:05:56.120
So that's going to pull the
lowest energy orbital toward the

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:56.829
oxygen.
 

00:05:56.829 --> 00:05:57.670
That'll be one thing.
 

00:05:57.670 --> 00:06:00.329
We expect it to be bigger,
top-heavy.

00:06:00.329 --> 00:06:00.939
Okay?
 

00:06:00.939 --> 00:06:04.199
What else, about how the top
will look?

00:06:04.199 --> 00:06:07.350
How will it be different from
if it were a CH_3?

00:06:07.350 --> 00:06:08.680
Yes, Alex?
 

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:10.579
I can't hear very well.
 

00:06:10.579 --> 00:06:11.329
Student:  Oxygen has
lone pairs.

00:06:11.329 --> 00:06:12.949
Prof: Oxygen has lone
pairs.

00:06:12.949 --> 00:06:15.180
Now, how is that going to
change things?

00:06:15.180 --> 00:06:18.437
Or another way of saying the
same thing is it has only one

00:06:18.437 --> 00:06:19.579
hydrogen up there.
 

00:06:19.579 --> 00:06:21.990
How's that going to change it,
do you think?

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:23.160
You have to speak up.
 

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:24.319
Student:  It's not going
to be symmetrical.

00:06:24.319 --> 00:06:25.500
Prof: It's not going to
be symmetrical.

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:30.689
Which way is it going to be
distorted to be unsymmetrical?

00:06:30.689 --> 00:06:31.829
You have to speak up.
 

00:06:31.829 --> 00:06:33.440
Student:  Towards the
electron pair.

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:35.690
Prof: Toward the
electron pair did you say?

00:06:35.690 --> 00:06:36.209
I couldn't hear.
 

00:06:36.209 --> 00:06:37.269
Student:  Away from
hydrogen.

00:06:37.269 --> 00:06:39.629
Prof: Away from hydrogen?
 

00:06:39.629 --> 00:06:41.639
Well how about -- the proton
goes out;

00:06:41.639 --> 00:06:45.490
does it bring electrons with
it, or does it repel electrons,

00:06:45.490 --> 00:06:46.339
the proton?
 

00:06:46.339 --> 00:06:46.970
Speak up.
 

00:06:46.970 --> 00:06:47.810
Student:  It brings them.
 

00:06:47.810 --> 00:06:50.095
Prof: It pulls,
so it should distort toward the

00:06:50.095 --> 00:06:50.569
hydrogen.
 

00:06:50.569 --> 00:06:52.293
So here's what it looks like.
 

00:06:52.293 --> 00:06:52.709
Right?
 

00:06:52.709 --> 00:06:54.745
It's top-heavy,
as Angela said,

00:06:54.745 --> 00:06:57.800
and it's distorted out toward
the hydrogen;

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:00.709
there are no protons pulling it
to the top left.

00:07:00.709 --> 00:07:03.266
And you see the same thing
end-on there,

00:07:03.266 --> 00:07:04.250
on the right.
 

00:07:04.250 --> 00:07:07.060
Okay, this is the next orbital.
 

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.610
What does that look like?
 

00:07:09.610 --> 00:07:12.060
Obviously you can peek in the
middle and see.

00:07:12.060 --> 00:07:16.016
It's obviously a 2p_z
orbital, with the node across

00:07:16.016 --> 00:07:16.920
the middle.
 

00:07:16.920 --> 00:07:17.310
Okay?
 

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:18.379
In both cases.
 

00:07:18.379 --> 00:07:22.089
Now the ethane case is
symmetrical.

00:07:22.089 --> 00:07:23.829
The other case is unsymmetrical.
 

00:07:23.829 --> 00:07:25.449
Why is it unsymmetrical?
 

00:07:25.449 --> 00:07:29.464
Because the first orbital
pulled electrons to the top.

00:07:29.464 --> 00:07:30.069
Right?
 

00:07:30.069 --> 00:07:33.545
So the next- in the next
orbital, electrons aren't going

00:07:33.545 --> 00:07:35.819
to want to be at the top so
much,

00:07:35.819 --> 00:07:37.959
because they're going to be
repelled by the other electrons;

00:07:37.959 --> 00:07:40.928
so there'll be more toward the
bottom, because the first ones

00:07:40.928 --> 00:07:41.819
went to the top.
 

00:07:41.819 --> 00:07:44.410
Okay?
 

00:07:44.410 --> 00:07:47.610
Okay, then here's the next
orbital.

00:07:47.610 --> 00:07:50.420
You can see there are energies
marching up here.

00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:53.769
The lowest one was s,
then 2p_z,

00:07:53.769 --> 00:07:56.971
now 2p_x,
if we define the horizontal

00:07:56.971 --> 00:07:59.949
axis here on the left as the x
axis.

00:07:59.949 --> 00:08:03.084
So again, it's what you expect,
and it's pulled out,

00:08:03.084 --> 00:08:06.836
stretched vertically from being
a dumbbell by where the nuclei

00:08:06.836 --> 00:08:07.389
went.
 

00:08:07.389 --> 00:08:11.718
And here's 2p_y,
which we can see more clearly

00:08:11.718 --> 00:08:14.466
on the right,
perpendicular to the

00:08:14.466 --> 00:08:15.800
2p_x.
 

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:16.800
Okay?
 

00:08:16.800 --> 00:08:22.161
And notice that it's obviously
so, that the methanol orbital

00:08:22.161 --> 00:08:25.434
will be less symmetric,
in all cases,

00:08:25.434 --> 00:08:27.980
than the one for ethane.
 

00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:31.007
But still we can recognize the
nodes, because they must go that

00:08:31.007 --> 00:08:31.300
way.
 

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:35.344
It must be no nodes,
one node of three different

00:08:35.344 --> 00:08:36.980
kinds, and so on.
 

00:08:36.980 --> 00:08:40.158
Okay, now this is 3s.
 

00:08:40.158 --> 00:08:43.240
You notice it has -- the node
that we don't see,

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:47.120
the one that's down near the
nuclei,

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:49.090
in fact two nodes down near the
nuclei,

00:08:49.090 --> 00:08:51.668
one for each of the heavy atoms.
 

00:08:51.668 --> 00:08:54.861
But then this now has another
spherical node,

00:08:54.861 --> 00:08:57.330
or approximately spherical
node.

00:08:57.330 --> 00:09:01.048
So we have that extra red lump
in the middle on the top,

00:09:01.048 --> 00:09:02.740
or blue, in the middle.
 

00:09:02.740 --> 00:09:05.804
Just to review,
what's the difference between

00:09:05.804 --> 00:09:06.850
red and blue?
 

00:09:06.850 --> 00:09:10.169
On the top, the computer
decided to draw it with red in

00:09:10.169 --> 00:09:10.970
the middle.
 

00:09:10.970 --> 00:09:13.580
On the bottom it decided to
draw it with blue in the middle.

00:09:13.580 --> 00:09:17.350
What do those colors mean?
 

00:09:17.350 --> 00:09:18.519
Yes, Cathy?
 

00:09:18.519 --> 00:09:19.418
Student:  Positive and
negative signs.

00:09:19.418 --> 00:09:20.620
Prof: The mean positive
and negative.

00:09:20.620 --> 00:09:21.759
So which one is right?
 

00:09:21.759 --> 00:09:24.922
Should it be positive in the
middle or negative in the

00:09:24.922 --> 00:09:25.460
middle?
 

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:29.090
Student:  Positive.
 

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:29.940
Prof: Positive is a
guess.

00:09:29.940 --> 00:09:30.778
Wilson, what do you say?
 

00:09:30.778 --> 00:09:31.460
Student:  It doesn't
matter.

00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:32.178
Prof: Why not?
 

00:09:32.178 --> 00:09:33.740
Student:  Because it's
not really positive or negative;

00:09:33.740 --> 00:09:36.379
it's just kind of a phase of it.
 

00:09:36.379 --> 00:09:37.941
Prof: Yes,
it's the sign of the wave

00:09:37.941 --> 00:09:38.350
function.
 

00:09:38.350 --> 00:09:40.990
But you can multiply the wave
function by minus one,

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:43.269
any constant,
and it's just as good as it was

00:09:43.269 --> 00:09:43.840
before.
 

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:46.614
So it's arbitrary,
and the computer was arbitrary

00:09:46.614 --> 00:09:48.058
in choosing the colors.
 

00:09:48.058 --> 00:09:51.027
I think there's actually a
function that I could've changed

00:09:51.027 --> 00:09:53.740
it, if I'd thought to do so,
so they'd be the same.

00:09:53.740 --> 00:09:57.519
But actually it tells a story
if I leave them different.

00:09:57.519 --> 00:09:59.740
Okay, so here's the next one.
 

00:09:59.740 --> 00:10:02.782
Now this is -- if you look on
the left now,

00:10:02.782 --> 00:10:07.200
it's more clear where the nodes
are, that that's a d_xz

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:08.070
orbital.
 

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:14.042
The name 'xz' means that
the product of x and z appears

00:10:14.042 --> 00:10:16.097
in the wave function.
 

00:10:16.097 --> 00:10:16.980
Right?
 

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:21.558
So when both x and z are
positive, then the product is

00:10:21.558 --> 00:10:25.308
positive;
on the top right, red. Right?

00:10:25.308 --> 00:10:28.155
When x is negative,
and z is positive,

00:10:28.155 --> 00:10:30.232
the top left,
it's negative,

00:10:30.232 --> 00:10:32.080
the product of them.
 

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:35.690
So that's why it has the name
xz.

00:10:35.690 --> 00:10:39.398
Okay, and there's d_yz,
which you see on the right,

00:10:39.398 --> 00:10:40.960
turned ninety degrees.
 

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:44.562
And here's the d_z^2,
which is that thing that has a

00:10:44.562 --> 00:10:46.798
doughnut that goes around the
middle.

00:10:46.798 --> 00:10:47.419
Right?
 

00:10:47.419 --> 00:10:49.490
It's hard to see the doughnut.
 

00:10:49.490 --> 00:10:50.049
Can you see?
 

00:10:50.049 --> 00:10:51.340
It's blue on top.
 

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:54.370
You can easily see the red on
the top left,

00:10:54.370 --> 00:10:57.039
which is what's blue in the
middle;

00:10:57.039 --> 00:10:58.908
the sign has changed. Right?
 

00:10:58.908 --> 00:11:01.509
But the doughnut is highly
distorted,

00:11:01.509 --> 00:11:04.620
because as you go around,
first a proton on the top pulls

00:11:04.620 --> 00:11:06.344
it up,
then a proton on the bottom

00:11:06.344 --> 00:11:07.629
pulls it down,
then up, down.

00:11:07.629 --> 00:11:11.306
So it's like a crown,
the doughnut has been made into

00:11:11.306 --> 00:11:15.053
a crown around the end,
by the protons pulling in that

00:11:15.053 --> 00:11:15.620
way.
 

00:11:15.620 --> 00:11:16.360
Okay.
 

00:11:16.360 --> 00:11:19.899
Then here's the 3p_z.
 

00:11:19.899 --> 00:11:24.068
So it has the horizontal nodal
plane, but also it has a

00:11:24.068 --> 00:11:27.312
spherical node,
which you can see in either

00:11:27.312 --> 00:11:28.779
picture really.
 

00:11:28.779 --> 00:11:29.970
Okay?
 

00:11:29.970 --> 00:11:32.168
Then here's the 3p _y
orbital,

00:11:32.168 --> 00:11:34.080
which again has that spherical
node,

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:37.019
but now the planar node,
or approximately planar node,

00:11:37.019 --> 00:11:39.509
is vertical instead of
horizontal.

00:11:39.509 --> 00:11:43.969
So say on the top right there
you have red on the right and

00:11:43.969 --> 00:11:45.428
blue on the left.
 

00:11:45.428 --> 00:11:49.346
There's a vertical node over
which it changes sign,

00:11:49.346 --> 00:11:51.070
going right to left.
 

00:11:51.070 --> 00:11:54.559
Or here's the 3_px.
 

00:11:54.559 --> 00:11:59.976
Or here's the 3d_xy;
which you don't see so well

00:11:59.976 --> 00:12:02.460
here;
well, but if you turned it down

00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:03.230
