00:14:59.129 --> 00:15:02.700
And next?
 

00:15:02.700 --> 00:15:03.889
Where will you go next?
 

00:15:03.889 --> 00:15:05.668
Steve, what do you say?
 

00:15:05.668 --> 00:15:08.090
The 1s of fluorine is
taken.

00:15:08.090 --> 00:15:10.000
The 1s of oxygen is
taken.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.679
Where do we want to go next?
 

00:15:12.679 --> 00:15:14.308
Pardon me?
 

00:15:14.308 --> 00:15:16.220
Student:  One of the
carbons.

00:15:16.220 --> 00:15:18.450
Prof: Ah, which carbon?
 

00:15:18.450 --> 00:15:19.830
Student:  The left
carbon.

00:15:19.830 --> 00:15:20.940
Prof: Why?
 

00:15:20.940 --> 00:15:23.696
Student:  Because it's
closer to the fluorine than the

00:15:23.696 --> 00:15:24.110
oxygen.
 

00:15:24.110 --> 00:15:28.090
Prof: And what does the
proximity have to do with it?

00:15:28.090 --> 00:15:33.658
The proximity means that the
electrons that are on that atom

00:15:33.658 --> 00:15:38.009
will have been drawn toward --
and we'll talk about this more

00:15:38.009 --> 00:15:40.269
later --
will have been drawn toward the

00:15:40.269 --> 00:15:41.769
fluorine and the oxygen.
 

00:15:41.769 --> 00:15:44.976
Therefore that atom will have
fewer electrons,

00:15:44.976 --> 00:15:46.827
or lower electron density.
 

00:15:46.827 --> 00:15:47.470
Right?
 

00:15:47.470 --> 00:15:51.440
Therefore, it's a better place
for other electrons to go.

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:51.950
Okay?
 

00:15:51.950 --> 00:15:55.243
So you'd expect the next one to
be the middle carbon.

00:15:55.243 --> 00:15:55.750
Right!
 

00:15:55.750 --> 00:15:58.155
And finally,
of course, it's going to be the

00:15:58.155 --> 00:16:00.619
second carbon,
the one that's remote from the

00:16:00.619 --> 00:16:03.250
electronegative,
high nuclear charge atoms.

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:06.480
Okay, now we've done all the
