00:16:23.480 --> 00:16:26.350
Prof: Yes,
it has no nodes;

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:29.340
except it actually has little
nodes down near the nucleus,

00:16:29.340 --> 00:16:32.121
because it's actually more like
a 2s orbital in that

00:16:32.121 --> 00:16:34.308
respect,
because of the core electrons.

00:16:34.308 --> 00:16:37.538
So it has tiny nodes that we
don't see around the nuclei.

00:16:37.538 --> 00:16:41.220
But it has no nodes within the
valence;

00:16:41.220 --> 00:16:42.759
big orbitals that we're looking
at.

00:16:42.759 --> 00:16:44.798
So it's like an s
orbital.

00:16:44.798 --> 00:16:45.308
Right?
 

00:16:45.308 --> 00:16:48.952
And it's big where the nuclear
charge is big,

00:16:48.952 --> 00:16:50.029
as you say.
 

00:16:50.029 --> 00:16:51.330
Okay?
 

00:16:51.330 --> 00:16:56.710
What's the next one going to
look like?

00:16:56.710 --> 00:17:01.889
Any ideas?
 

00:17:01.889 --> 00:17:02.889
Pardon me?
 

00:17:02.889 --> 00:17:03.370
Student:  Towards the
oxygen.

00:17:03.370 --> 00:17:06.926
Prof: Toward the oxygen.
 

00:17:06.926 --> 00:17:10.140
Will it also have no nodes?
 

00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:10.333
No.
 

00:17:10.333 --> 00:17:13.240
The next highest orbital has to
have a node.

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:14.538
Where do you think the node
will be?

00:17:14.538 --> 00:17:17.579
What orbital will it look like,
sort of?

00:17:17.579 --> 00:17:19.328
It'll be highly distorted.
 

00:17:19.328 --> 00:17:21.960
But what -- if this is the s
orbital, right?

00:17:21.960 --> 00:17:26.180
What's going to be next?
 

00:17:26.180 --> 00:17:27.450
Elizabeth?
 

00:17:27.450 --> 00:17:30.250
Student:  It's as if
it's switched but with a planar

00:17:30.250 --> 00:17:31.119
node in between.
 

00:17:31.119 --> 00:17:32.839
Prof: Oh let's see.
 

00:17:32.839 --> 00:17:34.338
Right!
 

00:17:34.338 --> 00:17:37.317
So the first one was -- you
were right Russell that this one

00:17:37.317 --> 00:17:38.630
should be big on oxygen.
 

00:17:38.630 --> 00:17:42.490
But notice it's like a p
orbital, it has that horizontal

00:17:42.490 --> 00:17:45.170
node, because it's higher
kinetic energy.

00:17:45.170 --> 00:17:45.690
Okay?
 

00:17:45.690 --> 00:17:49.123
And then this one,
that's on the carbons,

00:17:49.123 --> 00:17:49.809
right?
 

00:17:49.809 --> 00:17:50.380
Mostly.
 

00:17:50.380 --> 00:17:54.038
But it's a p_y,
it has a vertical node.

00:17:54.038 --> 00:17:57.695
So it's negative say on the
fluorine and oxygen and positive

00:17:57.695 --> 00:17:58.750
on the carbons.
 

00:17:58.750 --> 00:18:02.344
Or if we rotate this one around
a horizontal axis to look at it

00:18:02.344 --> 00:18:04.337
from the side,
it looks like that,

00:18:04.337 --> 00:18:07.309
and you can see that it's a
p_y kind of orbital.

00:18:07.309 --> 00:18:08.009
Elizabeth?
 

00:18:08.009 --> 00:18:09.690
Student:  I'm just
asking a point of clarification.

00:18:09.690 --> 00:18:11.538
These aren't technically
p orbitals,

00:18:11.538 --> 00:18:11.890
right?
 

00:18:11.890 --> 00:18:13.980
We're just saying they're
analogous to them.

00:18:13.980 --> 00:18:15.119
Prof: They're analogous
to p orbitals;

00:18:15.119 --> 00:18:18.420
because it has to be the same.
 

00:18:18.420 --> 00:18:22.363
The orbitals must go in order
of the number of nodes.

00:18:22.363 --> 00:18:22.970
Right?
 

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:25.410
So the same thing is in an atom
or in a molecule.

00:18:25.410 --> 00:18:27.170
You go from no nodes to one
node.

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:29.924
And there are three ways of
getting one node:

00:18:29.924 --> 00:18:33.683
spherical or distorted sphere,
planes, or distorted planes if

00:18:33.683 --> 00:18:36.440
the nuclei are pulled around;
and so on.

00:18:36.440 --> 00:18:39.680
So they're really very much
like the atomic orbitals.

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:42.170
Okay, or this one.
 

00:18:42.170 --> 00:18:46.074
Now that's an interesting one
because that's like a hybrid

00:18:46.074 --> 00:18:46.759
orbital.
 

00:18:46.759 --> 00:18:48.368
It looks like the orbital up
here.

00:18:48.368 --> 00:18:50.240
It's a mixture of s with
p.

00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:52.029
Did everybody see how that is?
 

00:18:52.029 --> 00:18:55.286
It's a big sort of blue lobe on
the top and a small red one on

00:18:55.286 --> 00:18:55.980
the bottom.
 

00:18:55.980 --> 00:18:58.630
And also the next one is the
other one,

00:18:58.630 --> 00:19:00.720
the hybrid that points the
other direction,

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:02.809
another combination of the
s and the p,

00:19:02.809 --> 00:19:04.859
that points down.
 

00:19:04.859 --> 00:19:06.980
Okay?
 

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:09.619
And then this one looks like
d_xy again.

00:19:09.619 --> 00:19:10.078
Right?
 

00:19:10.078 --> 00:19:14.470
It's sort of a cloverleaf with
two nodes.

00:19:14.470 --> 00:19:16.701
Okay, so that's all I want to
do with that,

00:19:16.701 --> 00:19:18.720
and we won't go any further
with it.

00:19:18.720 --> 00:19:21.808
This is just an interesting way
of looking at how --

00:19:21.808 --> 00:19:24.865
that molecular orbitals are
really just like atomic

00:19:24.865 --> 00:19:27.161
orbitals,
and have energies for the same

00:19:27.161 --> 00:19:28.993
reason,
except the potential energy

00:19:28.993 --> 00:19:31.874
gets screwed up by breaking the
nucleus and pulling pieces

00:19:31.874 --> 00:19:34.733
around,
but in an understandable way,

00:19:34.733 --> 00:19:38.308
and the nodes get distorted
because of this.

00:19:38.308 --> 00:19:43.126
Okay now, now we're getting
into really -- we just looked at

00:19:43.126 --> 00:19:46.720
this view, at the single united
atom view.

00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:49.737
But the other view is the one
that's going to be more

00:19:49.737 --> 00:19:52.116
generalizable,
and that's the one where we

00:19:52.116 --> 00:19:53.161
looked at bonding.
 

00:19:53.161 --> 00:19:53.798
Right?
 

00:19:53.798 --> 00:19:57.374
So you have to probe a little
harder to get a qualitative

00:19:57.374 --> 00:20:00.118
understanding of what chemical
bonds are.

00:20:00.118 --> 00:20:03.647
And that's what we're going to
do now by choosing a higher

00:20:03.647 --> 00:20:06.308
contour with which to look at a
molecule.

00:20:06.308 --> 00:20:10.647
Now, true molecular orbitals,
to the extent that orbitals are

00:20:10.647 --> 00:20:14.769
true all together -- why aren't
they true all together;

00:20:14.769 --> 00:20:18.880
why aren't orbitals true all
together?

00:20:18.880 --> 00:20:20.358
Yes, Alex?
 

00:20:20.358 --> 00:20:21.640
Student:  Because you
have multiple electrons.

00:20:21.640 --> 00:20:22.740
Prof: Because you have
many electrons;

00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:25.675
you can't have independent
electrons, you can't have

00:20:25.675 --> 00:20:26.308
orbitals.
 

00:20:26.308 --> 00:20:29.048
But we're approximating things
by orbitals,

00:20:29.048 --> 00:20:32.130
trying to take electron
interaction into account in a

00:20:32.130 --> 00:20:35.329
sort of a left-handed way by
Self-Consistent Field,

00:20:35.329 --> 00:20:36.420
or something like that.
 

00:20:36.420 --> 00:20:39.605
Because it's much easier if we
can divide the whole into a

00:20:39.605 --> 00:20:41.560
bunch of parts,
each of which we can

00:20:41.560 --> 00:20:42.400
understand.
 

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:44.900
So, to the extent that
molecular orbitals are true --

00:20:44.900 --> 00:20:46.358
the kinds of things I've just
been showing you,

00:20:46.358 --> 00:20:50.738
calculated with my laptop --
they extend over the whole

00:20:50.738 --> 00:20:54.358
molecule;
they're not local. Right?

00:20:54.358 --> 00:20:57.878
Except like the 1s of
fluorine was local,

00:20:57.878 --> 00:21:01.250
but mostly they go over the
whole molecule.

00:21:01.250 --> 00:21:05.230
But bonds are thought of,
and have always been thought

00:21:05.230 --> 00:21:08.608
of, as interactions between
pairs of atoms.

00:21:08.608 --> 00:21:14.378
So we want to divide things
completely differently and look

00:21:14.378 --> 00:21:18.655
at the bonds now,
at pairwise LCAO molecular

00:21:18.655 --> 00:21:19.950
orbitals.
 

00:21:19.950 --> 00:21:22.240
Now what's an LCAO?
 

00:21:22.240 --> 00:21:26.032
It's a sum, or a linear
combination.

00:21:26.032 --> 00:21:26.900
Right?
 

00:21:26.900 --> 00:21:30.220
A weighted sum of atomic
orbitals.

00:21:30.220 --> 00:21:31.460
So here's an example.
 

00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:34.400
Î¨, which is an orbital --
what's it a function of?

00:21:34.400 --> 00:21:35.690
Student:  Position.
 

00:21:35.690 --> 00:21:36.650
Prof: Position of what?
 

00:21:36.650 --> 00:21:37.269
Student:  One electron.
 

00:21:37.269 --> 00:21:37.940
Prof: One electron.
 

00:21:37.940 --> 00:21:40.220
So it's a function of
x_1,y_1,z_1;

00:21:40.220 --> 00:21:42.630
we're talking just about
electron one.

00:21:42.630 --> 00:21:46.644
So the wave function for
electron one we say is

00:21:46.644 --> 00:21:51.359
1/âˆš2 times one
atomic orbital plus another

00:21:51.359 --> 00:21:52.669
atomic orbital.
 

00:21:52.669 --> 00:21:53.630
Right?
 

00:21:53.630 --> 00:21:58.170
Now, have you ever seen adding
orbitals like that before?

00:21:58.170 --> 00:22:01.960
That's what hybridization is;
we added s and p.

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:04.877
But this is different,
because when we added s

00:22:04.877 --> 00:22:08.366
and p before,
they were on the same nucleus,

00:22:08.366 --> 00:22:12.248
and we did it to get a new
orbital for that particular

00:22:12.248 --> 00:22:15.367
nucleus for that atom;
to distort it one way or the

00:22:15.367 --> 00:22:17.300
other, for example,
or to rotate a p

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:17.669
orbital.
 

00:22:17.669 --> 00:22:18.130
Right?
 

00:22:18.130 --> 00:22:22.500
But this is very different,
because we're adding orbitals

00:22:22.500 --> 00:22:26.325
that are on different
nuclei: A, nucleus A,

00:22:26.325 --> 00:22:27.730
and nucleus B.
 

00:22:27.730 --> 00:22:30.598
See the difference?
 

00:22:30.598 --> 00:22:34.049
Adding is just -- wave
functions are numbers,

00:22:34.049 --> 00:22:36.088
we just add the numbers.
 

00:22:36.088 --> 00:22:38.323
But in the first case,
hybridization,

00:22:38.323 --> 00:22:41.240
those two functions were on the
same nucleus.

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:44.464
Now they're on different
nuclei, what we're adding

00:22:44.464 --> 00:22:45.190
together.
 

00:22:45.190 --> 00:22:50.266
Okay, now why is it sensible to
think that you might get

00:22:50.266 --> 00:22:55.990
pairwise molecular orbitals that
can be expressed like this?

00:22:55.990 --> 00:22:58.750
How do you interpret an orbital?
 

00:22:58.750 --> 00:23:00.990
Corey?
 

00:23:00.990 --> 00:23:01.859
What good is an orbital?
 

00:23:01.859 --> 00:23:03.710
What do you use it for?
 

00:23:03.710 --> 00:23:06.318
Student:  It's a
one-electron wave function.

00:23:06.318 --> 00:23:08.538
Prof: Well what do you
use it for?

00:23:08.538 --> 00:23:10.740
Student:  For
probability.

00:23:10.740 --> 00:23:14.108
Prof: And how do you get
probability?

00:23:14.108 --> 00:23:16.520
From the wave function -- if
you have the wave function,

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:18.319
how do you get the probability
density?

00:23:18.319 --> 00:23:19.019
Student:  You square it.
 

00:23:19.019 --> 00:23:20.108
Prof: You square it.
 

00:23:20.108 --> 00:23:25.278
So do you see why we have a
1/âˆš2 in this?

00:23:25.278 --> 00:23:28.843
Because when we square it,
that's going to be half,

00:23:28.843 --> 00:23:32.763
and we're going to get half of
atomic orbital A squared,

00:23:32.763 --> 00:23:35.329
and of atomic orbital B
squared;

00:23:35.329 --> 00:23:36.980
so it's a half of each of them.
 

00:23:36.980 --> 00:23:39.049
That's why we have
1/âˆš2.

00:23:39.049 --> 00:23:40.650
So let's go on with this.
 

00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:44.568
Suppose we have a hydrogen
molecule, and suppose that the

00:23:44.568 --> 00:23:48.068
nuclei are at a great distance
from one another.

00:23:48.068 --> 00:23:52.559
So far they don't interact,
or negligible interaction;

00:23:52.559 --> 00:23:53.890
they're very far apart.
 

00:23:53.890 --> 00:23:57.178
What would you expect the
lowest energy,

00:23:57.178 --> 00:24:00.720
one-electron wave function to
look like?

00:24:00.720 --> 00:24:05.746
One possibility is that the
electron could sit exactly

00:24:05.746 --> 00:24:08.685
halfway between the two nuclei?
 

00:24:08.685 --> 00:24:09.538
Right?
 

00:24:09.538 --> 00:24:12.565
Is that a reasonable place,
is that the low energy place

00:24:12.565 --> 00:24:13.390
for it to be?
 

00:24:13.390 --> 00:24:14.828
Lucas, what do you say?
 

00:24:14.828 --> 00:24:17.849
Student:  No,
because the added probability

00:24:17.849 --> 00:24:20.069
density there is not the
greatest.

00:24:20.069 --> 00:24:20.720
Prof: Why not?
 

00:24:20.720 --> 00:24:22.430
Student:  It needs to be
one or the other.

00:24:22.430 --> 00:24:24.407
Prof: Why shouldn't the
electrons sit -- if the two

00:24:24.407 --> 00:24:27.171
nuclei are this far apart;
and I don't mean two angstroms

00:24:27.171 --> 00:24:30.753
apart, I mean two meters apart
-- there's a proton here and a

00:24:30.753 --> 00:24:31.650
proton here.
 

00:24:31.650 --> 00:24:35.140
Is the electron most likely to
be here, halfway between?

00:24:35.140 --> 00:24:35.838
Student:  No.
 

00:24:35.838 --> 00:24:37.269
Prof: Where would it be
most likely?

00:24:37.269 --> 00:24:39.328
Student:  Probably
nearer to one of the two atoms.

00:24:39.328 --> 00:24:43.269
Prof: And which of the
two?

00:24:43.269 --> 00:24:44.538
&lt;&lt;Students speak over one
another&gt;&gt;

00:24:44.538 --> 00:24:46.960
Prof: Suppose you took
the long view.

00:24:46.960 --> 00:24:52.480
Suppose you averaged it over
eighteen zillion millennia --

00:24:52.480 --> 00:24:54.029
time averaged.
 

00:24:54.029 --> 00:24:57.682
Sometimes it would be near this
one, sometimes it would be near

00:24:57.682 --> 00:24:58.329
this one.
 

00:24:58.329 --> 00:24:59.088
Okay?
 

00:24:59.088 --> 00:25:01.210
What would it be if you took a
really long view?

00:25:01.210 --> 00:25:02.210
Student:  Both.
 

00:25:02.210 --> 00:25:05.519
Prof: And half here,
and half here.

00:25:05.519 --> 00:25:08.414
So the wave function,
when you square it,

00:25:08.414 --> 00:25:11.673
you want it to be half looking
like this atom,

00:25:11.673 --> 00:25:14.278
and half looking like this
atom.

00:25:14.278 --> 00:25:16.435
Then you see the time average.
 

00:25:16.435 --> 00:25:16.940
Right?
 

00:25:16.940 --> 00:25:19.637
It might take a long time to
achieve that average,

00:25:19.637 --> 00:25:22.887
because it'd take a long time
for the electron to tunnel two

00:25:22.887 --> 00:25:23.880
meters, right?
 

00:25:23.880 --> 00:25:26.111
But in the very,
very long time it would look

00:25:26.111 --> 00:25:26.720
like that.
 

00:25:26.720 --> 00:25:28.710
So we know what we want it to
look like.

00:25:28.710 --> 00:25:31.618
What we want is that the
probability density,

00:25:31.618 --> 00:25:34.308
the square of this one-electron
wave function,

00:25:34.308 --> 00:25:38.032
should look half of the time
like the atomic orbital A

00:25:38.032 --> 00:25:42.318
squared and half of the time
like atomic orbital B squared.

00:25:42.318 --> 00:25:45.349
So on time average it's half of
one and half of the other.

00:25:45.349 --> 00:25:47.509
Everybody with me?
 

00:25:47.509 --> 00:25:49.529
So that's what the -- yes, Nate?
 

00:25:49.529 --> 00:25:54.650
Student:  Why isn't
there a 2A -- or a 2AB?

00:25:54.650 --> 00:25:56.890
Prof: Oh,
because I'm telling you what it

00:25:56.890 --> 00:25:57.509
looks like.
 

00:25:57.509 --> 00:26:00.327
It's got to look half like this
and half like this.

00:26:00.327 --> 00:26:00.778
Right?
 

00:26:00.778 --> 00:26:04.538
So the square of it has to be
this.

00:26:04.538 --> 00:26:08.238
So all we have to do to find
the wave function is what,

00:26:08.238 --> 00:26:10.430
if we know what its square is?
 

00:26:10.430 --> 00:26:13.131
All we got to do is take the
square root and we've got the

00:26:13.131 --> 00:26:13.890
wave function.
 

00:26:13.890 --> 00:26:14.809
Bingo!
 

00:26:14.809 --> 00:26:20.170
There's the square root. Right?
 

00:26:20.170 --> 00:26:25.150
So that is a reasonable way to
write the wave function,

00:26:25.150 --> 00:26:28.746
1/âˆš2 (AO_A +
AO_B). Claire,

00:26:28.746 --> 00:26:30.960
you have a question.
 

00:26:30.960 --> 00:26:33.951
Student:  From my small
understanding,

00:26:33.951 --> 00:26:37.486
with the math that I've got --
