&gt;
 

00:28:26.028 --> 00:28:29.949
Okay, now your problem
is what happens if H_2 is at the

00:28:29.949 --> 00:28:31.170
bonding distance?
 

00:28:31.170 --> 00:28:34.220
What if they're only an
Angstrom apart?

00:28:34.220 --> 00:28:39.690
Now there should be a problem,
because A times B is not going

00:28:39.690 --> 00:28:42.788
to be negligible everywhere now.
 

00:28:42.788 --> 00:28:44.769
Okay, so now that's going to
come back.

00:28:44.769 --> 00:28:47.980
So now we got an error, right?
 

00:28:47.980 --> 00:28:49.829
Or do we?
 

00:28:49.829 --> 00:28:52.588
Let's think what that does.
 

00:28:52.588 --> 00:28:57.362
Okay, so we if approximate the
molecular orbital as the sum of

00:28:57.362 --> 00:29:00.804
atomic orbitals,
this way, then it looks very

00:29:00.804 --> 00:29:02.759
good near the nuclei.
 

00:29:02.759 --> 00:29:09.480
Because near A it looks like A;
near B it looks like B.

00:29:09.480 --> 00:29:14.080
And if we want to square it to
find the electron density,

00:29:14.080 --> 00:29:15.150
we do this.
 

00:29:15.150 --> 00:29:19.669
But if we then subtract,
what the atoms would give for

00:29:19.669 --> 00:29:21.288
electron density.
 

00:29:21.288 --> 00:29:25.373
Now what does this remind you
of, where we look at the total

00:29:25.373 --> 00:29:28.278
electron density and subtract
the atoms?

00:29:28.278 --> 00:29:29.180
Student:  Difference
density.

00:29:29.180 --> 00:29:31.123
Prof: So we're actually
looking for the difference

00:29:31.123 --> 00:29:31.470
density.
 

00:29:31.470 --> 00:29:33.038
Everybody with me on this?
 

00:29:33.038 --> 00:29:37.153
So we're going to subtract the
atoms, which is ½A^2 and

00:29:37.153 --> 00:29:37.962
½B^2.
 

00:29:37.962 --> 00:29:38.569
Right?
 

00:29:38.569 --> 00:29:42.088
If we subtract, what do we get?
 

00:29:42.088 --> 00:29:45.470
What do we get for a difference
density?

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:49.150
We get A times B.
 

00:29:49.150 --> 00:29:52.411
So we get the difference
electron density,

00:29:52.411 --> 00:29:54.480
which is due to overlap.
 

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:56.140
And what do I mean by overlap?
 

00:29:56.140 --> 00:30:00.925
I mean that is only important
in regions where both of them

00:30:00.925 --> 00:30:02.576
have a finite value.
 

00:30:02.576 --> 00:30:03.318
Right?
 

00:30:03.318 --> 00:30:06.460
The product of A and B is
negligible if A is zero;

00:30:06.460 --> 00:30:09.210
it's negligible if B is very,
very small.

00:30:09.210 --> 00:30:09.759
Right?
 

00:30:09.759 --> 00:30:13.194
So it's only where they
overlap, the two functions have

00:30:13.194 --> 00:30:15.548
simultaneous values,
that you care.

00:30:15.548 --> 00:30:21.358
Okay, now that thing,
the thing that's the bonding,

00:30:21.358 --> 00:30:25.390
the difference density,
is really a byproduct --

00:30:25.390 --> 00:30:28.868
that's a little bit of a pun
because it's a product --

00:30:28.868 --> 00:30:32.380
but it's a byproduct of
squaring the sum --

00:30:32.380 --> 00:30:34.279
of what Claire didn't like
about it.

00:30:34.279 --> 00:30:38.152
So the very thing you didn't
like is what's going to give

00:30:38.152 --> 00:30:39.950
rise to bonding density.
 

00:30:39.950 --> 00:30:44.019
Isn't that neat?
 

00:30:44.019 --> 00:30:47.838
Okay, but notice that here
we're multiplying A times B.

00:30:47.838 --> 00:30:50.500
But this is a completely
different instance of

00:30:50.500 --> 00:30:52.567
multiplying from what we had
before.

00:30:52.567 --> 00:30:53.160
Right?
 

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:55.596
Before we multiplied two
orbitals to try to get a

00:30:55.596 --> 00:30:57.068
two-electron wave function.
 

00:30:57.068 --> 00:31:00.032
This has nothing to do with
this, because both of these are

00:31:00.032 --> 00:31:03.743
functions of the same electron;
it's like one electron that

00:31:03.743 --> 00:31:05.318
we're squaring here.
 

00:31:05.318 --> 00:31:08.162
So this A times B,
this product,

00:31:08.162 --> 00:31:11.828
this overlap,
comes from the squaring.

00:31:11.828 --> 00:31:15.119
It was when we squared it that
we got that.

00:31:15.119 --> 00:31:18.608
Okay?
 

00:31:18.608 --> 00:31:21.180
Now, because we have this extra
term,

00:31:21.180 --> 00:31:24.338
we have not only
½(A^2+B^2),

00:31:24.338 --> 00:31:28.259
which would -- what's the
probability of A^2^( )summed

00:31:28.259 --> 00:31:30.401
over all space,
or integrated,

00:31:30.401 --> 00:31:31.559
if it's normalized?
 

00:31:31.559 --> 00:31:32.339
Students:  One.
 

00:31:32.339 --> 00:31:33.089
Prof: And this one?
 

00:31:33.089 --> 00:31:33.990
Students:  One.
 

00:31:33.990 --> 00:31:35.559
Prof: And what's this
whole quantity?

00:31:35.559 --> 00:31:36.130
Students:  One.
 

00:31:36.130 --> 00:31:37.618
Prof: One,
because of the half.

00:31:37.618 --> 00:31:40.711
But actually we've got it
bigger than that,

00:31:40.711 --> 00:31:43.583
because we added the overlap
term to it.

00:31:43.583 --> 00:31:44.318
Right?
 

00:31:44.318 --> 00:31:46.038
So it's actually not going to
be half;

00:31:46.038 --> 00:31:48.895
it'll have to be something a
little less than half,

00:31:48.895 --> 00:31:52.210
so that it'll sum up to one,
if we want to normalize it.

00:31:52.210 --> 00:31:52.750
Okay?
 

00:31:52.750 --> 00:31:55.640
So there's going to be those
less than halves there.

00:31:55.640 --> 00:31:56.779
Okay.
 

00:31:56.779 --> 00:31:59.078
Now what does that do?
 

00:31:59.078 --> 00:32:01.390
That shifts electron density,
right?

00:32:01.390 --> 00:32:05.479
We're taking electron density
away from where the nuclei are,

00:32:05.479 --> 00:32:08.272
from A^2 and B^2,
and where's the electron

00:32:08.272 --> 00:32:09.500
density going?
 

00:32:09.500 --> 00:32:12.898
Because we're using less than
half to begin with,

00:32:12.898 --> 00:32:15.519
we're taking electron density
away.

00:32:15.519 --> 00:32:18.817
There's going to be -- we're
subtracting more than was there

00:32:18.817 --> 00:32:19.767
at the beginning.
 

00:32:19.767 --> 00:32:20.269
Right?
 

00:32:20.269 --> 00:32:23.076
Which means that we're going to
have negative electron density

00:32:23.076 --> 00:32:24.180
in the difference map.
 

00:32:24.180 --> 00:32:26.089
Electrons are going away from
the atoms.

00:32:26.089 --> 00:32:28.369
Where are they going to?
 

00:32:28.369 --> 00:32:29.720
Student:  Into it.
 

00:32:29.720 --> 00:32:31.952
Prof: Into the region
where there's overlap.

00:32:31.952 --> 00:32:32.308
Right?
 

00:32:32.308 --> 00:32:36.450
So they go away from there,
into the overlap region.

00:32:36.450 --> 00:32:39.868
So this is just like what we
were seeing with X-ray.

00:32:39.868 --> 00:32:43.032
Okay, so that overlap,
the A times B term,

00:32:43.032 --> 00:32:45.039
is what creates bonding.
 

00:32:45.039 --> 00:32:46.769
And we've seen this before.
 

00:32:46.769 --> 00:32:50.493
Remember when you have wells
far apart, the wave function is

00:32:50.493 --> 00:32:53.785
the sum of the two;
we saw this in one-dimension.

00:32:53.785 --> 00:32:54.259
Right?
 

00:32:54.259 --> 00:32:56.174
But if they come close
together, you get a wave

00:32:56.174 --> 00:32:58.743
function that looks like that,
which we looked before,

00:32:58.743 --> 00:33:01.028
just from the point of view of
the energy,

00:33:01.028 --> 00:33:03.528
and saw that that would
stabilize the particle,

00:33:03.528 --> 00:33:05.922
because it's got less
curvature, less kinetic energy.

00:33:05.922 --> 00:33:06.288
Right?
 

00:33:06.288 --> 00:33:10.741
But also the electron density
grows in the middle.

00:33:10.741 --> 00:33:11.470
Right?
 

00:33:11.470 --> 00:33:15.816
So from the point of view of
the electron distribution,

00:33:15.816 --> 00:33:19.598
that was the glue holding the
atoms together.

00:33:19.598 --> 00:33:22.298
So it's held together,
both because the energy goes

00:33:22.298 --> 00:33:24.892
down and because you put this
glue in the middle,

00:33:24.892 --> 00:33:27.430
which is what causes the energy
to go down.

00:33:27.430 --> 00:33:28.150
Okay?
 

00:33:28.150 --> 00:33:29.460
So that's bonding.
 

00:33:29.460 --> 00:33:31.348
And remember we also had this.
 

00:33:31.348 --> 00:33:35.223
So as the energy went up in the
middle one, the energy is lower

00:33:35.223 --> 00:33:37.598
here than it was in the atoms
apart.

00:33:37.598 --> 00:33:41.865
So the nuclei push one another
apart now, without the glue in

00:33:41.865 --> 00:33:44.710
the middle, and that was
anti-bonding.

00:33:44.710 --> 00:33:46.567
So we've seen it before in
one-dimension,

00:33:46.567 --> 00:33:48.608
but it's true in
three-dimensions as well.

00:33:48.608 --> 00:33:50.180
Now let's think about this
again.

00:33:50.180 --> 00:33:53.779
So here's atom A.
 

00:33:53.779 --> 00:33:58.680
Now where is the square of that
function significant?

00:33:58.680 --> 00:34:00.950
Is it significant there?
 

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:01.650
No.
 

00:34:01.650 --> 00:34:04.990
Is it significant there?
 

00:34:04.990 --> 00:34:06.849
Yes, it's a little bit
significant at least.

00:34:06.849 --> 00:34:09.889
How about there?
 

00:34:09.889 --> 00:34:12.389
A little bit. Right?
 

00:34:12.389 --> 00:34:13.480
Okay.
 

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:17.429
Now suppose we have another
atomic orbital there.

00:34:17.429 --> 00:34:23.610
Now, where is the product
significant, of A times B?

00:34:23.610 --> 00:34:24.880
Okay?
 

00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:28.150
So is the product A times B
significant there?

00:34:28.150 --> 00:34:30.320
No.
 

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:39.460
Is it significant there?
 

00:34:39.460 --> 00:34:40.989
Nick, what do you say?
 

00:34:40.989 --> 00:34:41.829
Student:  No.
 

00:34:41.829 --> 00:34:44.030
Prof: Why not?
 

00:34:44.030 --> 00:34:44.820
Speak up.
 

00:34:44.820 --> 00:34:46.099
Student:  It's very
small near A.

00:34:46.099 --> 00:34:47.130
Prof: What's very small?
 

00:34:47.130 --> 00:34:49.110
Student:  The value of A.
 

00:34:49.110 --> 00:34:50.018
Prof: No,
no.

00:34:50.018 --> 00:34:52.315
The value of A there is
something -- we said that

00:34:52.315 --> 00:34:55.090
before, when we were looking
only at A -- it's not very big

00:34:55.090 --> 00:34:56.909
but there's a significant value.
 

00:34:56.909 --> 00:34:58.630
But how about the product?
 

00:34:58.630 --> 00:34:59.119
Josh?
 

00:34:59.119 --> 00:35:00.230
Student:  The value of B
is very small.

00:35:00.230 --> 00:35:02.170
Prof: The value of B is
very small there.

00:35:02.170 --> 00:35:04.170
So the product is going to be
very small.

00:35:04.170 --> 00:35:06.719
How about there?
 

00:35:06.719 --> 00:35:08.130
Student: There's going
to be a change.

00:35:08.130 --> 00:35:09.969
Prof: Ah,
now they're equal;

00:35:09.969 --> 00:35:11.630
halfway between they're equal.
 

00:35:11.630 --> 00:35:14.983
So both of them are a little
bit small, but their product is

00:35:14.983 --> 00:35:16.007
still significant.
 

00:35:16.007 --> 00:35:16.518
Right?
 

00:35:16.518 --> 00:35:19.922
Only in this region,
where they overlap,

00:35:19.922 --> 00:35:22.539
is that product significant.
 

00:35:22.539 --> 00:35:23.190
Okay.
 

00:35:23.190 --> 00:35:25.784
So at the center,
notice that the number

00:35:25.784 --> 00:35:29.711
Î¨_A assigns and the
number Î¨_B assigns

00:35:29.711 --> 00:35:31.309
are the same number.
 

00:35:31.309 --> 00:35:35.525
So 2(Î¨_A Î¨_B) is
as large as

00:35:35.525 --> 00:35:40.143
(Î¨_A)^2+(Î¨_B)^2;
because Î¨_A times

00:35:40.143 --> 00:35:42.469
Î¨_B is the same as
(Î¨_A)^2.

00:35:42.469 --> 00:35:45.847
So the electron density is
nearly doubled in the middle

00:35:45.847 --> 00:35:49.539
from what it would've been if it
had just been two atoms.

00:35:49.539 --> 00:35:51.684
So that's the region of
significant overlap,

00:35:51.684 --> 00:35:53.280
and that's what we care about.
 

00:35:53.280 --> 00:35:55.922
So the overlap integral,
summing this produc -- or

00:35:55.922 --> 00:35:59.320
integrating it -- over all that
space, that's a certain density.

00:35:59.320 --> 00:35:59.860
Right?
 

00:35:59.860 --> 00:36:01.489
We squared in order to get
that.

00:36:01.489 --> 00:36:01.909
Right?
 

00:36:01.909 --> 00:36:03.920
That's part of the density.
 

00:36:03.920 --> 00:36:07.130
So we sum that,
the density that comes from

00:36:07.130 --> 00:36:09.271
that product,
over all space,

00:36:09.271 --> 00:36:12.559
and that's called the overlap
integral.

00:36:12.559 --> 00:36:15.992
If the atoms are very far
apart, the overlap integral is

00:36:15.992 --> 00:36:17.179
essentially zero.
 

00:36:17.179 --> 00:36:19.574
If the atoms are close
together, the overlap orbital

00:36:19.574 --> 00:36:23.447
will be finite,
and the better the -- the more

00:36:23.447 --> 00:36:27.755
the orbitals overlap,
the bigger the overlap

00:36:27.755 --> 00:36:29.650
integral, obviously.
 

00:36:29.650 --> 00:36:33.889
And that measures the net
change that arises on bonding,

00:36:33.889 --> 00:36:37.360
the difference density,
as we've just seen.

00:36:37.360 --> 00:36:42.320
Now let's look at some
theoretical examples here.

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:47.240
So let's look at the total
electron density as calculated

00:36:47.240 --> 00:36:52.338
for two -- adding two 1s
orbitals of hydrogen at the

00:36:52.338 --> 00:36:55.239
appropriate distance for H_2.
 

00:36:55.239 --> 00:36:57.894
This was this was done forty
years ago and published in the

00:36:57.894 --> 00:36:59.590
Israel Journal of
Chemistry.

00:36:59.590 --> 00:37:02.235
Okay now, and here's -- so on
the left we have the total

00:37:02.235 --> 00:37:04.639
electron density that you'd
calculate from that.

00:37:04.639 --> 00:37:10.969
A very simple thing:
1/âˆš2(A+B).

00:37:10.969 --> 00:37:13.936
And you square it,
and you get the density,

00:37:13.936 --> 00:37:16.833
and that's the density,
contoured at 0.025

00:37:16.833 --> 00:37:20.579
electrons/cubic a_o,
the unit of distance.

00:37:20.579 --> 00:37:24.260
Okay, now, on the right is the
difference density.

00:37:24.260 --> 00:37:28.132
So from that thing on the left
we've subtracted the atomic

00:37:28.132 --> 00:37:30.920
orbital, the atomic electron
densities.

00:37:30.920 --> 00:37:33.380
And you see exactly what you
expect.

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:37.400
It builds up in the middle,
where there's overlap,

00:37:37.400 --> 00:37:40.190
and at the expense of the
atoms.

00:37:40.190 --> 00:37:40.849
Yes Russell?
 

00:37:40.849 --> 00:37:42.829
Student:  Shouldn't it
be H_2^+ ion?

00:37:42.829 --> 00:37:47.411
Prof: Oh,
I think it's the H_2_

00:37:47.411 --> 00:37:52.440
molecule,
I'm sure it's the H_2_.

00:37:52.440 --> 00:37:55.262
They aren't so
fantastically different,

00:37:55.262 --> 00:37:58.599
because the two electrons are
in the same orbital;

00:37:58.599 --> 00:38:00.219
two electrons can be in the
same orbital.

00:38:00.219 --> 00:38:02.059
So one'll be twice as big as
the other.

00:38:02.059 --> 00:38:04.260
Qualitatively they'll look very
similar.

00:38:04.260 --> 00:38:06.268
And I think this is the H_2
molecule;

00:38:06.268 --> 00:38:08.489
but it might be the ion,
I'm not sure.

00:38:08.489 --> 00:38:13.409
Okay, at any rate the contours
on the right are much smaller.

00:38:13.409 --> 00:38:16.650
Remember, difference density is
much smaller than total density.

00:38:16.650 --> 00:38:20.320
So what you see is that it's
contoured at 0.004.

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:22.878
So you have one,
two, three, four,

00:38:22.878 --> 00:38:24.119
five contours.
 

00:38:24.119 --> 00:38:26.655
So you get up,
in the middle,

00:38:26.655 --> 00:38:30.280
to 0.02 electrons per cubic
angstrom .

00:38:30.280 --> 00:38:33.960
That's how much bonding has
changed things,

00:38:33.960 --> 00:38:35.449
at the maximum.
 

00:38:35.449 --> 00:38:38.980
Okay, now the energy that's
calculated,

00:38:38.980 --> 00:38:42.190
with this very,
very, very crude wave function,

00:38:42.190 --> 00:38:45.621
just one half --
1/âˆš2 times the sum

00:38:45.621 --> 00:38:47.739
of the two atomic orbitals.
 

00:38:47.739 --> 00:38:54.019
The energy, you calculate that,
is 92.9% of the true energy.

00:38:54.019 --> 00:38:57.079
That's pretty darn good, right?
 

00:38:57.079 --> 00:39:01.014
But almost all of that energy
that you calculate was already

00:39:01.014 --> 00:39:03.150
present in the separate atoms.
 

00:39:03.150 --> 00:39:05.530
We're not interested in the
energy of the separate atoms,

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:08.900
we're interested in how much it
changes when you make a bond,

00:39:08.900 --> 00:39:12.050
which is a small difference
between large numbers.

00:39:12.050 --> 00:39:16.023
So it turns out that although
we're within 7% of the true

00:39:16.023 --> 00:39:18.664
total energy,
this simple model only

00:39:18.664 --> 00:39:22.632
calculates about 50% of the
change in energy that came from

00:39:22.632 --> 00:39:24.960
putting them together -- right?
 

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:28.329
-- which is much smaller.
 

00:39:28.329 --> 00:39:32.202
Okay, so high accuracy is
required to calculate a correct

00:39:32.202 --> 00:39:34.070
value of the bond energy.
 

00:39:34.070 --> 00:39:35.510
This simple thing won't do it.
 

00:39:35.510 --> 00:39:38.838
Well it's in the right
direction, you're halfway there,

00:39:38.838 --> 00:39:40.565
so it's a pretty good start.
 

00:39:40.565 --> 00:39:41.119
Right?
 

00:39:41.119 --> 00:39:44.721
But to do the difference,
as in the same way you needed

00:39:44.721 --> 00:39:47.789
high precision to do X-ray
difference maps,

00:39:47.789 --> 00:39:49.610
you need better orbitals than
this,

00:39:49.610 --> 00:39:51.730
if you want to calculate good
bond energies.

00:39:51.730 --> 00:39:54.829
So you need to make the
orbitals better.

00:39:54.829 --> 00:39:55.329
Okay?
 

00:39:55.329 --> 00:39:59.724
Now -- so but already we can
take heart that the very crudest

00:39:59.724 --> 00:40:03.894
model shows most,
52%, of the energy of the bond,

00:40:03.894 --> 00:40:08.434
and it shows the electron
density building up by 0.02

00:40:08.434 --> 00:40:11.489
electrons per cubic bohr radius.
 

00:40:11.489 --> 00:40:16.001
And what we saw qualitatively
was there was a shift from the

00:40:16.001 --> 00:40:19.059
atom to the bond,
of electron density.

00:40:19.059 --> 00:40:22.909
Okay, now we can adjust the
molecular orbital to get a

00:40:22.909 --> 00:40:25.889
better approximation of the true
thing.

00:40:25.889 --> 00:40:28.666
How will we know when we've
adjusted it and it's gotten

00:40:28.666 --> 00:40:29.130
better?
 

00:40:29.130 --> 00:40:32.867
If we adjust it and get a
lower, calculate a lower average

00:40:32.867 --> 00:40:35.106
energy --
I should've said a lower

00:40:35.106 --> 00:40:37.965
average energy,
because if we don't have a true

00:40:37.965 --> 00:40:41.420
wave function we get different
values for the total energy;

00:40:41.420 --> 00:40:44.565
the kinetic won't exactly
offset the potential as you move

00:40:44.565 --> 00:40:45.780
from place to place.
 

00:40:45.780 --> 00:40:48.380
But if you get the lowest
average energy,

00:40:48.380 --> 00:40:51.750
then that is,
by definition almost,

00:40:51.750 --> 00:40:55.856
more realistic,
because you can easily prove

00:40:55.856 --> 00:41:00.920
that the true energy is the
lowest possible energy;

00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:02.860
that makes a certain amount of
sense.

00:41:02.860 --> 00:41:06.639
The lowest possible calculated
energy is the true energy.

00:41:06.639 --> 00:41:10.699
So if you change your wave
function and get a lower average

00:41:10.699 --> 00:41:13.289
energy, you're closer to the
truth.

00:41:13.289 --> 00:41:14.018
Okay?
 

00:41:14.018 --> 00:41:17.429
That's called the Variational
Principle.

00:41:17.429 --> 00:41:22.409
Okay, so here we've changed the
form of the molecular orbital.

00:41:22.409 --> 00:41:23.730
And how did we change it?
 

00:41:23.730 --> 00:41:26.289
What does a 1s orbital
look like?

00:41:26.289 --> 00:41:30.960
Kate, do you remember the form
for a 1s atomic orbital?

00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:31.539
I can't hear.
 

00:41:31.539 --> 00:41:32.610
Student:  A sphere.
 

00:41:32.610 --> 00:41:34.670
Prof: Angularly it's a
sphere.

00:41:34.670 --> 00:41:37.739
How does it change as you go
out, do you remember?

00:41:37.739 --> 00:41:41.260
How does it depend on
Ï ?

00:41:41.260 --> 00:41:44.590
The same way they all depend on
Ï .

00:41:44.590 --> 00:41:47.119
Anybody remember?
 

00:41:47.119 --> 00:41:49.018
Prof: e^-Ï .
 

00:41:49.018 --> 00:41:52.159
So it falls off exponentially
at a certain rate.

00:41:52.159 --> 00:41:54.197
And that rate,
how fast it falls off,

00:41:54.197 --> 00:41:56.349
is determined by the nuclear
charge.

00:41:56.349 --> 00:41:56.869
Okay?
 

00:41:56.869 --> 00:42:01.507
Now one way to change that
shape would be change how fast

00:42:01.507 --> 00:42:02.583
it falls off.
 

00:42:02.583 --> 00:42:03.329
Right?
 

00:42:03.329 --> 00:42:05.449
It wouldn't be correct for the
atom anymore.

00:42:05.449 --> 00:42:07.940
We've already got the correct
solution for the atom.

00:42:07.940 --> 00:42:11.423
But we could change the shape
of the thing by changing how

00:42:11.423 --> 00:42:13.320
fast that exponent falls off.
 

00:42:13.320 --> 00:42:17.391
And we could vary that,
in the molecule,

00:42:17.391 --> 00:42:21.880
using one half --
1/âˆš2(A+B).

00:42:21.880 --> 00:42:24.706
But those A+B are no
longer true atomic functions,

00:42:24.706 --> 00:42:26.980
they're a little fatter,
a little skinnier.

00:42:26.980 --> 00:42:27.530
Okay?
 

00:42:27.530 --> 00:42:30.257
And we can change how fat or
skinny it is,

00:42:30.257 --> 00:42:33.119
until we get the lowest
molecular energy.

00:42:33.119 --> 00:42:36.989
See, that's a way you can vary
it and find the best value.

00:42:36.989 --> 00:42:40.210
And that's what was done here
to optimize the exponent.

00:42:40.210 --> 00:42:42.681
And now you get a total
electron density that looks

00:42:42.681 --> 00:42:44.659
essentially the same as it did
before.

00:42:44.659 --> 00:42:48.007
And if you look at the
difference density,

00:42:48.007 --> 00:42:51.030
how has it changed,
if you do this?

00:42:51.030 --> 00:42:54.139
First, notice that the energy
got lower.

00:42:54.139 --> 00:42:58.518
We're now to 73% of the
lowering of the bond energy.

00:42:58.518 --> 00:43:00.820
So the total energy's gotten
lower, it's better.

00:43:00.820 --> 00:43:04.320
And how has the electron
density changed?

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:06.039
It got higher in the middle.
 

00:43:06.039 --> 00:43:09.592
Because what we did was spread
the exponent out a little bit,

00:43:09.592 --> 00:43:11.960
so you had more overlap in the
middle.

00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:13.369
Okay?
 

00:43:13.369 --> 00:43:16.206
So this wouldn't have been good
for the single atom,

00:43:16.206 --> 00:43:18.820
to spread it out,
but it gives a better function

00:43:18.820 --> 00:43:19.989
for the molecule.
 

00:43:19.989 --> 00:43:21.679
And it's still very,
very simple.

00:43:21.679 --> 00:43:25.677
And what you see it did is it
increases the bonding density

00:43:25.677 --> 00:43:27.539
and the bonding strength.
 

00:43:27.539 --> 00:43:30.320
You get a larger shift from the
atoms to the bond.

00:43:30.320 --> 00:43:35.847
Now, how else could you change
the shape of the atomic orbital

00:43:35.847 --> 00:43:39.018
in order to increase the
overlap;

00:43:39.018 --> 00:43:42.126
some way other than making a
single exponential and having it

00:43:42.126 --> 00:43:43.369
get fatter or thinner?
 

00:43:43.369 --> 00:43:44.699
Can you think of some other way?
 

00:43:44.699 --> 00:43:47.429
Here you have an atomic
orbital, a sphere,

00:43:47.429 --> 00:43:51.291
and you want to change its
shape so that it overlaps better

00:43:51.291 --> 00:43:51.956
over here.
 

00:43:51.956 --> 00:43:52.690
Right?
 

00:43:52.690 --> 00:43:56.833
How could you change the shape
of an atomic orbital,

00:43:56.833 --> 00:44:00.001
without doing really gross
damage to it,

00:44:00.001 --> 00:44:04.469
making it a cube or something
like that, or a line?

00:44:04.469 --> 00:44:08.052
How could you change it so it
looked pretty much still like an

00:44:08.052 --> 00:44:10.755
atom did, has a lot of the
virtues of the atom,

00:44:10.755 --> 00:44:12.460
but is shifted over here?
 

00:44:12.460 --> 00:44:17.949
Sam?
 

00:44:17.949 --> 00:44:18.610
I can't hear.
 

00:44:18.610 --> 00:44:20.730
Student:  Can't you just
allow the electrons to shift?

00:44:20.730 --> 00:44:22.851
Prof: Yes,
how am I going to write a

00:44:22.851 --> 00:44:25.324
function that allows the
electrons to shift in the

00:44:25.324 --> 00:44:26.789
direction I want them to?
 

00:44:26.789 --> 00:44:27.750
Lexy?
 

00:44:27.750 --> 00:44:29.070
Student:  You could
hybridize it.

00:44:29.070 --> 00:44:30.539
Prof: Hybridize it!
 

00:44:30.539 --> 00:44:32.420
We could hybridize to shift the
electrons.

00:44:32.420 --> 00:44:33.780
So that's the next one.
 

00:44:33.780 --> 00:44:37.503
So here we're going to --
instead of this we're going to

00:44:37.503 --> 00:44:38.518
hybridize it.
 

00:44:38.518 --> 00:44:41.041
Now, this particular
calculation did the

00:44:41.041 --> 00:44:44.664
hybridization and also did a
little self-consistent field

00:44:44.664 --> 00:44:45.699
calculation.
 

00:44:45.699 --> 00:44:50.719
And the hybridization left it
96.7% 1s.

00:44:50.719 --> 00:44:53.940
So essentially it's still a
normal 1s orbital.

00:44:53.940 --> 00:44:57.480
But they added .6% of
2s, which expanded it a

00:44:57.480 --> 00:45:01.367
little bit, because 2s is
-- goes further out than

00:45:01.367 --> 00:45:02.340
1s.
 

00:45:02.340 --> 00:45:06.349
And they added 2.7% of
2p.

00:45:06.349 --> 00:45:10.550
Now why was 2p much more
helpful than 2s?

00:45:10.550 --> 00:45:12.730
Lucas?
 

00:45:12.730 --> 00:45:14.619
Student:  It has those
lobes.

00:45:14.619 --> 00:45:17.001
Prof: Yes,
so it takes density from one

00:45:17.001 --> 00:45:18.800
side and shifts it to the other.
 

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:21.570
In fact, this is precisely what
we saw before.

00:45:21.570 --> 00:45:29.186
Notice what it did was -- how
much it increased the density in

00:45:29.186 --> 00:45:30.809
the middle.
 

00:45:30.809 --> 00:45:33.429
And notice now,
it's not taking electron

00:45:33.429 --> 00:45:37.126
density away from the nuclei,
which was a good place for

00:45:37.126 --> 00:45:38.469
electrons to be.
 

00:45:38.469 --> 00:45:40.349
Where does it take it away from?
 

00:45:40.349 --> 00:45:41.760
Student: The left one.
 

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:44.561
Prof: Out beyond the
nuclei, and shift it to the

00:45:44.561 --> 00:45:45.030
middle.
 

00:45:45.030 --> 00:45:47.420
So even before,
when it was an atom --

00:45:47.420 --> 00:45:50.679
here's the nucleus,
a certain distance out here,

00:45:50.679 --> 00:45:54.030
and a certain distance out
here, were the same in energy,

00:45:54.030 --> 00:45:55.360
for that atom.
 

00:45:55.360 --> 00:45:59.634
Now we've taken it from a place
which is -- out here,

00:45:59.634 --> 00:46:00.949
and put it here.
 

00:46:00.949 --> 00:46:01.690
Right?
 

00:46:01.690 --> 00:46:03.639
Great idea.
 

00:46:03.639 --> 00:46:05.840
Well done Lexy.
 

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:06.780
So there's what it looked like.
 

00:46:06.780 --> 00:46:09.170
Remember, if it's 100 percent
at 1s,

00:46:09.170 --> 00:46:11.684
it looks like that,
and if you change it to be

00:46:11.684 --> 00:46:14.827
hybridized that way,
with Atom-in-a-Box,

00:46:14.827 --> 00:46:16.686
it looks like this.
 

00:46:16.686 --> 00:46:17.469
Right?
 

00:46:17.469 --> 00:46:20.759
It's not much shift,
but it shifts from the left to

00:46:20.759 --> 00:46:23.260
the right, and gives better
overlap.

00:46:23.260 --> 00:46:29.233
Okay, but it requires the atom
to be a little bit less happy as

00:46:29.233 --> 00:46:34.920
an atom, because it's partly
2s and 2p now.

00:46:34.920 --> 00:46:38.186
The electrons are further from
the nucleus, but you make up for

00:46:38.186 --> 00:46:39.820
that by having a better bond.
 

00:46:39.820 --> 00:46:43.429
Okay, now notice that didn't
change the energy very much.

00:46:43.429 --> 00:46:46.820
It went from 73% to 76%. Right?
 

00:46:46.820 --> 00:46:49.882
We were already about the right
energy, but it changed the

00:46:49.882 --> 00:46:52.300
density a lot,
to be what we want it to be.

00:46:52.300 --> 00:46:57.242
Okay, so there's a much bigger
shift, and it's now from beyond

00:46:57.242 --> 00:46:59.349
the nucleus into the bond.
 

00:46:59.349 --> 00:47:00.079
Right?
 

00:47:00.079 --> 00:47:04.268
And now we're going to do the
last thing.

00:47:04.268 --> 00:47:07.005
We've done SCF already,
but now you have to do a higher

00:47:07.005 --> 00:47:09.489
level calculation that'll do
correlation, take the

00:47:09.489 --> 00:47:11.820
correlation of the electrons
into account.

00:47:11.820 --> 00:47:16.641
And if you add some correlation
calculation to this,

00:47:16.641 --> 00:47:19.480
you now get 90% of the bond.
 

00:47:19.480 --> 00:47:21.978
If you did complete
correlation, you'd get 100% of

00:47:21.978 --> 00:47:22.539
the bond.
 

00:47:22.539 --> 00:47:27.445
What does it mean to do a
calculation with complete

00:47:27.445 --> 00:47:28.820
correlation?
 

00:47:28.820 --> 00:47:30.900
It means you don't have an
error anymore,

00:47:30.900 --> 00:47:32.980
you've used a really good
calculation.

00:47:32.980 --> 00:47:36.581
So already at this level,
that was done fifty years ago

00:47:36.581 --> 00:47:38.849
almost, you get 90% of the bond.
 

00:47:38.849 --> 00:47:42.143
And the bond density notice,
what about the electron

00:47:42.143 --> 00:47:42.789
density?
 

00:47:42.789 --> 00:47:44.130
Student:  No change.
 

00:47:44.130 --> 00:47:45.570
Prof: It hasn't really
changed.

00:47:45.570 --> 00:47:48.757
All that happened was that the
electrons kept apart from one

00:47:48.757 --> 00:47:51.349
another, but the average density
was the same.

00:47:51.349 --> 00:47:53.849
So already, with just that
hybridization,

00:47:53.849 --> 00:47:58.150
we got very close to the truth
in electron distribution,

00:47:58.150 --> 00:48:01.663
and three-quarters of the way
to the truth in how strong a

00:48:01.663 --> 00:48:02.280
bond is.
 

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:04.289
So not a bad approximation.
 

00:48:04.289 --> 00:48:06.181
So hybridization,
to give better overlap,

00:48:06.181 --> 00:48:07.079
is a great thing.
 

00:48:07.079 --> 00:48:10.637
So the density wasn't changed,
but you got a much better

00:48:10.637 --> 00:48:11.219
energy.
 

00:48:11.219 --> 00:48:13.619
And how so?
 

00:48:13.619 --> 00:48:16.811
Because the electrons kept
apart from one another,

00:48:16.811 --> 00:48:18.699
when you allow correlation.
 

00:48:18.699 --> 00:48:23.210
Okay, so here's a pairwise
atomic orbital:

00:48:23.210 --> 00:48:27.788
1/âˆš2(A+B);
and you can use hybridized

00:48:27.788 --> 00:48:28.280
orbitals.
 

00:48:28.280 --> 00:48:30.856
And the virtues are it's very
easy to formulate and to

00:48:30.856 --> 00:48:31.489
understand.
 

00:48:31.489 --> 00:48:35.159
And it looks like atoms,
especially when you get down

00:48:35.159 --> 00:48:36.429
near the nuclei.
 

00:48:36.429 --> 00:48:39.516
And you don't want that to
change because that's the main

00:48:39.516 --> 00:48:40.730
event for electrons.
 

00:48:40.730 --> 00:48:43.193
You get much more energy
forming atoms,

00:48:43.193 --> 00:48:46.175
as we saw before,
than you do making new bonds,

00:48:46.175 --> 00:48:48.510
once you have the atoms
already.

00:48:48.510 --> 00:48:49.860
Okay.
 

00:48:49.860 --> 00:48:52.518
It builds up electron density
between the nuclei,

00:48:52.518 --> 00:48:55.289
through overlap,
which is the source of bonding.

00:48:55.289 --> 00:49:00.630
It smoothes Î¨,
to lower the kinetic energy.

00:49:00.630 --> 00:49:04.190
And then there's a pedantic
footnote here that actually

00:49:04.190 --> 00:49:07.159
there's a thing called the
Virial Theorem,

00:49:07.159 --> 00:49:09.230
which I'm not going to stress
you with,

00:49:09.230 --> 00:49:12.469
but that little bit there,
it happens to be true.

00:49:12.469 --> 00:49:16.302
But still we have the proper
understanding of what's going

00:49:16.302 --> 00:49:16.639
on.
 

00:49:16.639 --> 00:49:20.505
Hybridizing AOs provides
flexibility that gives you

00:49:20.505 --> 00:49:21.820
better overlap.
 

00:49:21.820 --> 00:49:25.043
And if you use all the H-like
Atomic Orbitals,

00:49:25.043 --> 00:49:28.985
you have perfect flexibility,
you can make any shape you

00:49:28.985 --> 00:49:29.630
want.
 

00:49:29.630 --> 00:49:32.150
Okay, but we're going to keep
it simple,

00:49:32.150 --> 00:49:35.929
use only 2s and
2p orbitals to hybridize,

00:49:35.929 --> 00:49:38.561
because that'll get you most of
the way there and it's much

00:49:38.561 --> 00:49:40.965
simpler,
rather than to try to mix

00:49:40.965 --> 00:49:43.480
5f orbitals into it also.
 

00:49:43.480 --> 00:49:45.110
Okay, so that's great.
 

00:49:45.110 --> 00:49:46.835
And when we square it,
we get this,

00:49:46.835 --> 00:49:49.219
which has the overlap part that
helps us out.

00:49:49.219 --> 00:49:51.641
We have the atoms,
plus the bond,

00:49:51.641 --> 00:49:54.820
which is the overlap,
that product part.

00:49:54.820 --> 00:49:59.039
But we could've done the same
thing to get the same product,

00:49:59.039 --> 00:50:02.233
as far as the atoms go,
if we'd used a minus sign

00:50:02.233 --> 00:50:05.230
instead of a plus sign in
combining things;

00:50:05.230 --> 00:50:08.545
although then we would've
changed the sign of the overlap

00:50:08.545 --> 00:50:09.019
thing.
 

00:50:09.019 --> 00:50:10.429
It would become minus.
 

00:50:10.429 --> 00:50:13.981
So we would change it from
being less than to being greater

00:50:13.981 --> 00:50:17.226
than, in order to have it be
normalized at the bottom.

00:50:17.226 --> 00:50:17.840
Right?
 

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:19.320
And that's the anti-bond.
 

00:50:19.320 --> 00:50:24.030
So we get both the bond and the
anti-bond by doing this.

00:50:24.030 --> 00:50:26.922
And now we're going to go on,
next time, to overlap,

00:50:26.922 --> 00:50:29.985
which we've already introduced,
and also the concept of

00:50:29.985 --> 00:50:30.949
energy-match.
 

00:50:30.949 --> 00:50:33.434
And when you put these two
together, you'll really

00:50:33.434 --> 00:50:34.500
understand bonding.
 

